15":"1215","1225":"1225","1224":"1224","Abt 1189":"circa 1189","1189":"1189","1254":"1254","about 1225":"circa 1225","about 1165":"circa 1165","Abt 1190":"circa 1190","Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, England","Westmorland, England":"Westmorland, England","Levens, Westmorland, England":"Levens, Westmorland, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Runnymede":"Runnymede, Queensland, Australië"},"en":{"about 1165–about 1225":"about 1165–about 1225","1165–1225":"1165–1225","1182–Male":"1182–Deceased","1170–Female":"1170–Deceased","1189–Male":"1189–Deceased","1190–1254":"1190–1254","1192–Male":"1192–Deceased","1220–Male":"1220–Deceased","1140–1184":"1140–1184","–Female":"Deceased","1190":"1190","about 1192":"about 1192","1220":"1220","1165":"1165","1184":"1184","1140":"1140","abt 1220":"about 1220","1182":"1182","1192":"1192","1170":"1170","June 1215":"June 1215","1215":"1215","1225":"1225","1224":"1224","Abt 1189":"about 1189","1189":"1189","1254":"1254","about 1225":"about 1225","about 1165":"about 1165","Abt 1190":"about 1190","Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, England","Westmorland, England":"Westmorland, England","Levens, Westmorland, England":"Levens, Westmorland, England, United Kingdom","Runnymede":"Runnymede, Queensland, Australia","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Redmayne,","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["English: locative name from Redmain (Cumb). The place, recorded as  <i>Rademan</i> in 1202, is named with Old English  <i>rēad</i> ‘red’ + an uncertain second element, perhaps a dialectal form of  <i>man</i> ‘cairn’."],"variants":[{"name":"Redman","meanings":["English: occupational name from Middle English <i>red</i> (Old English <i>hrēod</i>) ‘reed’ + <i>-man</i>, presumably for a thatcher or reed-cutter. Compare   Reeder  .","English: in southeastern England sometimes a topographic name perhaps for someone who lived by a clearing, from Middle English <i>rede</i> (Old English <i>rēod</i>, <i>rȳd</i>) ‘clearing’ + <i>man</i>.","English: habitational name from Redmain (Cumberland), from Old English <i>rēad</i> ‘red’ + an uncertain second element, perhaps a dialect form of <i>man</i> ‘cairn’."]},{"name":"Rothery","meanings":["English: apparently from an Anglicized form of the Welsh or Brittonic personal name <i>Rhydderch</i> (see   Roderick   and   Prothero  )."]},{"name":"Readman","meanings":["1  English:  see  Redmayne  .","2  English:  see  Redman  ."]}]},{"name":"Henry","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["A perennially popular given name, of Continental Germanic origin, from <i>haim</i> ‘home’ + <i>rīc</i> ‘power, ruler’. It was an Old French name, adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to Britain. It has been borne by eight kings of England. Not until the 17th century did the form <i>Henry</i> (as opposed to   Harry  ) become the standard vernacular form, mainly under the influence of the Latin form <i>Henricus</i> and French <i>Henri</i>."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705187,"age":50,"year":"1215","julianDay":2164830,"title":"Magna Carta","description":"King John of England agreed to a charter of rights called the Magna Carta. The document was originally drafted by the Archbishop of Canterbury to establish peace between King John and a group of rebel barons. The Magna Carta was completed in 1215 and is now considered to be one of the greatest constitutional documents of all time.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/education/medieval/magna-carta/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Magna Carta","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705188,"age":59,"year":"1224","julianDay":2168117,"title":"France Declares War on England","description":"France declared war on England as Louis VIII of France attacked Poitou and northern Gascony.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Sir Henry Redmayne, I was born about 1165, in Levens, Westmorland, En